Topic: Automobile price prediction¶

Predicting the price of used cars is one of the significant and interesting areas of analysis. As an increased demand in the second-hand car market, the business for both buyers and sellers has increased. this project we try to find the important features that influence the price of cars and make a model as accurate as possible to predict the price of any car.¶

Data Attributes , Range , Type¶

1. symboling: -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3. int¶

2. normalized-losses: continuous from 65 to 256. object¶

3. make: alfa-romero, audi, bmw, chevrolet, dodge, honda, object¶

isuzu, jaguar, mazda, mercedes-benz, mercury,¶

mitsubishi, nissan, peugot, plymouth, porsche,¶

renault, saab, subaru, toyota, volkswagen, volvo¶

4. fuel-type: diesel, gas. object¶

5. aspiration: std, turbo. object¶

6. num-of-doors: four, two. object¶

7. body-style: hardtop, wagon, sedan, hatchback, convertible. object¶

8. drive-wheels: 4wd, fwd, rwd. object¶

9. engine-location: front, rear. object¶

10. wheel-base: continuous from 86.6 120.9. float¶

11. length: continuous from 141.1 to 208.1. float¶

12. width: continuous from 60.3 to 72.3. float¶

13. height: continuous from 47.8 to 59.8. float¶

14. curb-weight: continuous from 1488 to 4066. float¶

15. engine-type: dohc, dohcv, l, ohc, ohcf, ohcv, rotor. object¶

16. num-of-cylinders: eight, five, four, six, three, twelve, two. object¶

17. engine-size: continuous from 61 to 326. float¶

18. fuel-system: 1bbl, 2bbl, 4bbl, idi, mfi, mpfi, spdi, spfi. object¶

19. bore: continuous from 2.54 to 3.94. object¶

20. stroke: continuous from 2.07 to 4.17. object¶

21. compression-ratio: continuous from 7 to 23. float¶

22. horsepower: continuous from 48 to 288. object¶

23. peak-rpm: continuous from 4150 to 6600. object¶

24. city-mpg: continuous from 13 to 49. int¶

25. highway-mpg: continuous from 16 to 54. int¶

26. price: continuous from 5118 to 45400. int¶

Formatting¶

Data formatting means bringing data into a common standard of expression that allows users to make meaningful comparison.¶

In our used car data-set, there’s a feature named “city-mpg” in the data-set, which refers to a car fuel consumption in miles per gallon unit. However, we don’t use such mpg, we want to convert those values to L/100km — the metric version. L / 100km = 235.21/ x mpg¶

In [9]:

11 21

13 20

15 16
In [10]:
automobile['city-mpg']=235/automobile['city-mpg']

# rename column
automobile.rename(columns={'city-mpg':'city-L/100KM'},inplace=True)

Binning¶

we use data binning to group a set of numerical values into a smaller number of bins to have a better understanding of the data distribution. In the actual car data-set, “price” is a numerical variable ranging from 5,188 to 45,400, it has 201 unique values. We can categorize them into 3 bins: low, medium, and high-priced cars.¶

In [17]:
binwidth=int((max(automobile['price'])-min(automobile['price']))/3)
In [18]:
bins=range(int(min(automobile['price'])),int(max(automobile['price'])),binwidth)
In [19]:
automobile['price-binned']=pd.cut(automobile['price'],bins,labels=["Low","Medium","High"])

Heatmap¶

A heat map can explain the correlation between the variables with the color intensity. It is a great way to plot the target variable over multiple variables and through this get visual clues of the relationship between variables and the target. As we now have to move into building machine learning models to automate our analysis, feeding the model with variables that meaningfully affect our target variable will improve our model’s prediction performance¶
